Adjust racks to top and middle position and preheat oven to 450 degrees. Wash and dry produce.

Quarter @lemon{1}. Cut @potatoes{12%ounce} into ½-inch-thick wedges.

Toss potatoes on a #baking sheet{} with a large drizzle of @olive oil{5%teaspoon} and a big pinch of @salt{} and @pepper{}. Spread out across sheet in a single layer.

Roast on top rack, tossing three-quarters of the way through, until golden brown, ~{25-30%minutes}.

While potatoes roast, in a #small bowl{}, combine @mayonnaise{6%tablespoon}, @garlic powder{1/4%tsp}, @truffle zest{1/4%tsp}, and a squeeze of lemon juice. (For 4 servings, use ½ tsp garlic powder, ½ tsp truffle zest, and two squeezes of lemon juice.)

> Be sure to measure truffle zest—we sent more.

In a separate small bowl, combine @ketchup{3%unit}, half the @balsamic glaze{2.5%teaspoon}, and half the @Dijon mustard{1%teaspoon} (you'll use the rest later).

Pat @bavette steak{10%ounce} dry with #paper towels{} and season all over with remaining @garlic powder{3/4%tsp}, @salt{}, and @pepper{}.

Heat a drizzle of @cooking oil{1%teaspoon} in a large, preferably ovenproof, pan over medium-high heat. Add steak and cook until browned but not cooked through, ~{2%minutes} per side. Remove pan from heat (keep steak in pan).

> If your pan isn't ovenproof, transfer steak to a #baking sheet{}.

Carefully transfer pan with steak to middle rack of oven; roast to desired doneness, ~{4-8%minutes}.

Transfer to a #cutting board{}; let rest for at least ~{5%minutes}.

While steak roasts, in a #large bowl{}, whisk together remaining mustard, @olive oil{1%tablespoon}, @sherry vinegar{1%teaspoon}, a pinch of @sugar{}, @salt{}, and @pepper{}. (Save remaining sherry vinegar for another use.)

Add @mixed greens{2%ounce}, @dried cherries{1%ounce}, @walnuts{1/2%ounce}, and half the @Parmesan cheese{3%tablespoon} to bowl with dressing; toss to combine. Taste and season with salt and pepper if desired.

Thinly slice steak against the grain.

Divide steak, potatoes, and salad between plates. Sprinkle remaining Parmesan over salad. Serve with any remaining lemon wedges on the side and truffle aioli and balsamic ketchup for dipping.

> Steak is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 145°.